CONTEXT Try21 IN ENGLISH

PURPOSE CONTEXT Try21 {+ Test left residual operator (/) with proper type checking and hierarchy-aware disambiguation. +}

{- PREDICTION based on Ampersand theory:

Test 1 (enrolled/requires): Should PASS
- enrolled[Student*Course] / requires[Course*Subject] 
- target(enrolled) = Course, source(requires) = Course → exact match
- Result: Student*Subject (matches shouldPass declaration)

Test 2 (enrolled/teaches): Likely to FAIL  
- enrolled[Student*Course] / teaches[Teacher*Subject]
- target(enrolled) = Course, source(teaches) = Teacher
- No clear relationship between Course and Teacher in the hierarchy
- The meet(Course,Teacher) is undefined, so type checking should fail

Test 3-4: Depend on Test 1, should PASS if Test 1 passes

Test 5 (enrolled/(requires/passed)): Likely to FAIL
- requires[Course*Subject] / passed[Student*Subject]
- target(requires) = Subject, source(passed) = Student  
- No relationship between Subject and Student defined
- Nested residual creates complex type constraints that likely won't resolve

Expected outcome: Test 1 should pass, Tests 2 and 5 likely to fail due to type mismatches.
-}

PATTERN Try21

-- Create concept hierarchies to test residual operators

CLASSIFY Student ISA Person
CLASSIFY Teacher ISA Person
CLASSIFY Course ISA Subject
CLASSIFY Course ISA Topic
CLASSIFY AdvancedCourse ISA Course

-- Basic relations for residual testing
RELATION enrolled[Student*Course]     -- Student enrolled in Course
RELATION teaches[Teacher*Subject]     -- Teacher teaches Subject  
RELATION passed[Student*Subject]      -- Student passed Subject
RELATION requires[Course*Subject]     -- Course requires Subject

-- Test relations for results
RELATION shouldPass[Student*Subject]  -- What a student should pass
RELATION competent[Student*Teacher]   -- Student competent with teachers

-- Auxiliary relations to force specific type contexts
RELATION studentOf[X*Student]         -- Forces Student context
RELATION courseOf[Y*Course]           -- Forces Course context
RELATION subjectOf[Z*Subject]         -- Forces Subject context

-- Test 1: Basic left residual - should work cleanly
-- enrolled[Student*Course] / requires[Course*Subject] = shouldPass[Student*Subject]
-- target(enrolled) = Course matches source(requires) = Course
RULE TestLeftResidual1: shouldPass = enrolled;requires
RULE TestLeftResidual2: shouldPass = enrolled/requires
RULE TestLeftResidual3: shouldPass = enrolled/requires~
{-
-- Test 2: Left residual with problematic hierarchy 
-- enrolled[Student*Course] / teaches[Teacher*Subject]
-- target(enrolled) = Course, source(teaches) = Teacher - no clear meet
RULE TestLeftResidualHierarchy: competent = enrolled/teaches

-- Test 3: Complex composition with left residual (depends on Test 1)
RULE TestLeftResidualComposition: result1 = studentOf;shouldPass
RELATION result1[X*Subject]

-- Test 4: Left residual in reverse composition (depends on Test 1)
RULE TestLeftResidualComposition2: result2 = shouldPass;subjectOf
RELATION result2[Student*Z]

-- Test 5: Nested residuals - complex type propagation
-- enrolled/(requires/passed) where requires/passed likely fails
RULE TestNestedResiduals: result3 = enrolled/(requires/passed)
RELATION result3[Student*Student]

-}
ENDPATTERN
ENDCONTEXT

{-
Purpose: Test left residual operator (/) implementation with expected failures

This test is designed to stress-test the left residual implementation:
- Test 1 should demonstrate correct basic residual operation
- Test 2 should reveal issues with unrelated concept hierarchies  
- Tests 3-4 test residuals in larger expressions
- Test 5 tests nested residual associativity with type mismatches

If the implementation is correct:
- Test 1 should succeed (clean type match)
- Tests 2 and 5 should fail with clear type error messages
- Tests 3-4 should succeed if Test 1 succeeds
-}
